          "title": "The anatomy of practical atheism (10:2-11)",
          "body": "Verses 2-11 constitute the longest sustained portrait of the wicked in the entire Psalter — nine verses of forensic character analysis. The psalmist is building a legal case, not merely venting. The portrait has three layers. First, the wicked man's inner theology: he does not seek God (10:4), all his thoughts are 'There is no God' (10:4), he believes himself permanently prosperous and immune from adversity (10:5-6), and he concludes that 'God has forgotten' and 'will never see it' (10:11). This is not theoretical atheism; it is the practical atheism of a man whose conduct assumes divine non-interference. Second, his corrupt speech: his mouth is full of curses, deceit, and oppression; mischief and wickedness lie under his tongue like concealed weapons (10:7). Third, his predatory violence: he lurks in hiding places, ambushes the innocent, and traps the afflicted as methodically as a lion stalking prey (10:8-10). The lion and net imagery makes the point that his violence is patient and systematic, not impulsive. What drives all three layers is pride — *gaavah* (10:2) and *govah* (10:4), swelling arrogance that has displaced God from the center of his moral universe. Tim Keller, in *The Songs of Jesus*, notes that practical atheism is not a philosophical position but a daily operating assumption, one that every human heart is capable of adopting whenever suffering appears to go unpunished."
