    "intro": "Psalm 10 is a lament-to-confidence psalm that works simultaneously as personal prayer, as theodicy (justifying God's ways in the face of evil), and as subversive counter-theology against the wicked man's practical atheism. The five movements below trace the psalm's argument from the opening complaint through the evidence-dossier on the oppressor, through the petition and the theological pivot, to the doxological resolution. The psalm's center of gravity is verse 14 — the assertion that God has seen — which quietly dismantles the nine-verse case the wicked man has built about divine amnesia.",
