        "excerpt": "Why do You stand afar off, O Lord? Why do You hide Yourself in times of trouble?",
        "body": "The psalm opens with a rhetorical question that is simultaneously a complaint and a confession of faith. To ask 'Why do You hide?' presupposes that God normally does not hide — that His nearness is the norm and His hiddenness the exception requiring explanation. The psalmist is not questioning whether God exists; he is questioning why the God who exists is not visible in the present crisis (*batstsarah* — a narrow, pressing trouble). This is a crucial distinction. Lament in the Psalter is not the language of doubt; it is the language of disappointed expectation, which is itself a form of faith.\n\nThe two 'Why?' questions (the Hebrew *lamah*, recurring at 10:13) are the psalm's rhetorical frame. They do not receive direct answers in the text. This is intentional. The psalm does not resolve the lament by explaining God's hiddenness; it resolves it by reasserting God's character (10:14-18). The pastoral implication is significant: not every 'Why?' gets an answer. What the afflicted person receives instead is a clearer vision of who God is — which proves sufficient.\n\nIn the canonical structure of the Psalter, this lament stands in direct sequence with Psalm 9's praise of God's past acts of judgment. The juxtaposition is theologically deliberate. The same God who 'avenges blood' and 'does not forget the cry of the afflicted' (Psalm 9:12) appears absent in Psalm 10. This is the Psalter's honest acknowledgment that God's people live in the tension between what He has done and what He appears to be doing now — between sacred memory and present silence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Lamah* (why) — the interrogative of bewildered faith, used throughout the Psalms of lament (cf. Psalm 22:1, 42:9, 44:23). *Batstsarah* (trouble, distress) — from *tsarar*, to be narrow, pressed, confined. The word conveys a crisis that closes in from all sides, leaving no human escape route."
