        "excerpt": "The wicked, in the haughtiness of his countenance, does not seek Him. All his thoughts are, 'There is no God.'",
        "body": "Verses 2-11 are the psalm's longest section and its most forensic. The psalmist is not simply describing a type but building a legal case before the divine Judge — presenting the evidence that demands a verdict. The evidence is organized in three concentric circles: the wicked man's inner theology (10:3-6), his corrupt speech (10:7), and his predatory actions (10:8-11). Each layer moves outward from what he thinks to what he says to what he does — the same pattern of moral deterioration Jesus traces in Mark 7:21-23.\n\nThe root sin is pride (*gaavah*, 10:2; *govah*, 10:4). Pride is not merely arrogance in the social sense but a theological displacement: the wicked man has moved himself to the center of his moral universe and pushed God to the periphery. The result is a peculiar form of atheism — not a philosophical denial of God's existence but a practical exclusion of God from operative reality. 'All his thoughts are, There is no God' (10:4) does not mean he is a creedal atheist; it means he lives, plans, and acts as though God is not watching, not remembering, and not requiring. His self-talk in 10:6, 11, and 13 — three times marked by *lev* ('to himself') — is the inner monologue of a man who has constructed a theology of divine inattention to license his violence.\n\nThe predatory imagery in 10:8-10 is among the most vivid in the Psalter. The wicked man sits in ambush near the villages (where the vulnerable are exposed), lurks like a lion in a thicket, and catches the afflicted in a net. The triple verb sequence — 'lurks... catches... draws him into his net' (10:9) — conveys methodical patience. This is not opportunistic crime but systematic exploitation. Peter Davids' comments on the letter of James 5:1-6 illuminate the same social pattern: the powerful who oppress the poor do so through structures and habits of predation, not merely isolated acts.\n\nThe nine-verse dossier ends with the wicked man's definitive theological claim: 'God has forgotten; He has hidden His face; He will never see it' (10:11). This is the claim the psalm exists to answer. Three assertions — forgotten, hidden, will never see — construct a theology of permanent divine amnesia. The psalmist's response at 10:14 demolishes all three with a single declaration.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gaavah* and *govah* (10:2, 4) — both from the root *ga'ah*, to rise up, to be lifted high. Together they make pride the poem's root sin. *Ayin elohim* (there is no God, 10:4) — literally 'no God' — a functional creedal statement lived out in conduct. *Arav* (to lie in wait, 10:9) — the hunter's posture of concealed waiting; used of military ambush in Joshua 8:4 and of wisdom calling in Proverbs 8:34 (the positive counterpart)."
