        "excerpt": "Arise, O Lord; O God, lift up Your hand. Do not forget the afflicted… You have seen it, for You have beheld mischief and vexation to take it into Your hand.",
        "body": "The petition begins at verse 12 with an imperative trio that reaches back into Israel's oldest liturgical memory: 'Arise, O Lord; lift up Your hand; do not forget.' 'Arise' (*qum*) is the war-cry of Numbers 10:35, voiced when the ark moved out in the wilderness: 'Rise up, O Lord! And let Your enemies be scattered.' The psalmist is summoning not a passive deity but the warrior-God of the Exodus — the one who visibly rose to scatter Israel's enemies. 'Lift up Your hand' (*nasa* *yad*) is the idiom for judicial and executive action — the raised hand of a judge pronouncing sentence, or a king executing a decree. 'Do not forget' (*shakhach*) directly inverts the wicked man's claim of 10:11. If the oppressor believes God has forgotten, the psalmist prays that God would prove that claim false by remembering — and acting.\n\nVerse 14 is the psalm's pivot and its most theologically dense sentence: 'You have seen it, for You have beheld mischief and vexation to take it into Your hand. The unfortunate commits himself to You; You have been the helper of the orphan.' Three things are affirmed. First, God has seen (*navat* — to look attentively, to behold with intention). Second, He has not merely seen but taken the mischief *into His hand* — He holds the evil, about to act on it. Third, the helpless person's act of self-commitment ('commits himself to You,' *azav* in the sense of entrusting, abandoning oneself to God's care) is met by God's established identity as 'the helper of the orphan.' The covenant history of God's care for the fatherless (Exodus 22:22-24; Deuteronomy 10:18; Psalm 68:5) is the psalmist's evidence that God will act now.\n\nThe petitions of verse 15 are specific and bold: 'Break the arm of the wicked and the evildoer; seek out his wickedness until You find none.' *Zeroa* (arm) is the symbol of concentrated strength — the tool of the oppressor's predation. The psalmist asks not for the oppressor's discomfort but for the disabling of his power. The verb *darash* ('seek out,' 10:15) is the same verb used in 10:4 (the wicked does not seek God) and 10:13 (the wicked believes God will not require, *darash*, an accounting). The irony is deliberate: the one who neither sought God nor believed God would seek him is himself exhaustively sought out by God.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qum* (arise, 10:12) — the Exodus-conquest war cry (Numbers 10:35; Psalm 68:1). *Navat* (You have beheld, 10:14) — to look attentively, to gaze at with intention; a stronger visual verb than simple *ra'ah*. *Azav* (commits himself, 10:14) — lexically the same root as 'forsake/abandon,' here used reflexively to mean 'entrust oneself entirely.' *Shavar* (break, 10:15) — to shatter, smash; used of breaking a yoke (Isaiah 9:4) or breaking bones."
