        "body": "Verse 16 is the theological climax of the psalm, stated in two parallel lines. 'The Lord is King forever and ever' — the Hebrew is minimalist, weighty, six words that assert the eternal sovereignty of Yahweh without qualification. The two temporal terms — *olam* (the vast expanse of time, indefinite past and future) and *ad* (perpetuity, the on-going without end) — span every temporal claim the wicked man has made about his own permanence. His boast of 10:6 ('throughout all generations I will not be moved') is the counterfeit claim; 10:16 is the authentic one, and it belongs to Yahweh alone.\n\nThe second line grounds the theological claim in historical fact: 'Nations have perished from His land.' This is not a wish but a past-tense declaration — the perfect form in Hebrew. The Canaanite kingdoms, the Egyptian empire, the nations of the ancient Near East that appeared invincible have been removed from the land Yahweh claimed as His own. The conquest narratives of Joshua and the exodus tradition are the evidentiary base. The psalmist's strategy is to place the wicked man of his own day in the same category as those nations — temporal powers whose apparent permanence was overturned by the eternal King.\n\nCalvin comments on this verse that the psalm 'sets the eternity of God's kingdom against all the pride of the world,' and that this is not triumphalism but grounded theological reasoning: if God's kingship has already displaced the mightiest nations of history, the arrogance of one predatory individual cannot ultimately stand. Douglas Moo, in his treatment of theodicy in the Pauline letters, notes the same logic in Romans 8:18 — present suffering is calibrated against the eternal weight of God's sovereign purposes, not against the apparent permanence of the present order.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Melekh* (King, 10:16) — the royal title applied to Yahweh in the great enthronement psalms (Psalms 93, 95-99). *Olam* — used 439 times in the OT; spans the full horizon of time in both directions. *Avad* (perished, have destroyed) — the same verb used of Israel's enemies throughout Deuteronomy (Deuteronomy 28:20; 30:18). *Erets* (land) — in the covenant context, specifically God's land, the territory He claimed and distributed (Psalm 37:11; Matthew 5:5 echoes this)."
