        "body": "The psalm's final movement (10:17-18) is the positive completion of the lament's opening questions. Verse 1 asked why God hides; verses 17-18 declare that He hears, inclines His ear, strengthens hearts, and vindicates. The lament is not left unanswered — but the answer is not an explanation of God's hiddenness; it is a disclosure of God's character and commitment.\n\nThree divine actions are promised in verse 17. First, 'You have heard the desire (*taavah*) of the humble (*anav*).' The word *taavah* (desire) is the same word used in 10:3 for the wicked man's craving — but here it describes the humble person's deep longing for deliverance. God hears the desire before it is even fully articulated as a request. Second, 'You will strengthen their heart' (*kun lev* — establish, make firm the inner person). The primary answer to lament is interior fortification — God's first work is in the heart of the one who suffers, not only in the circumstances that cause the suffering. Third, 'You will incline Your ear' — the attentive posture of a judge who leans toward the testimony of the plaintiff. The God who appeared afar off in verse 1 is now leaning toward the cry of the afflicted.\n\nVerse 18 names the beneficiaries and the outcome: to vindicate 'the orphan and the oppressed' (*yatom* and *dakh* — the fatherless and the crushed one), 'so that man who is of the earth will no longer cause terror.' The closing phrase is striking in its anthropology. *Enosh min ha-erets* — mortal man from the dust. The wicked oppressor who has dominated nine verses of the psalm is finally reduced to his true identity: he is *enosh*, frail mortal clay (cf. Psalm 8:4; Isaiah 51:12), taken from the earth and returning to it. Under the eternal King, such a man has no permanent power to terrorize. Jonathan Edwards, in his treatise *The Nature of True Virtue*, observed that all human cruelty is finally a symptom of the creature's usurpation of the place belonging to God — and that it ends when the creature is returned to his true creaturely proportion under the Creator.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Anav* (humble, 10:17) — the spiritually poor, the meek, the one whose spirit has been bent low by suffering and who has no recourse but God (cf. Psalm 37:11; Isaiah 61:1 — the anawim whom the Messiah anoints). *Kun lev* (strengthen the heart) — to establish, make firm; used of God stabilizing what would otherwise tremble. *Shaphat* (vindicate, 10:18) — to judge in favor of, to render a verdict that restores the wronged party. *Enosh* (man of the earth) — emphatic mortal frailty; deliberately placed at the psalm's close to reduce the oppressor to his proper scale."
